natural problem: What is the greatest common divisor of $654321$ and $543210$?

a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes a b :: nat
assumes h0 : "a = 654321"
and h1 : "b = 543210"
shows  "gcd a b = 3"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 What is the greatest common divisor of $654321$ and $543210$? The final Answer is 3
 ### Proof
 By the Euclidean Algorithm, \begin{align}\text{gcd}\,(654321,543210) &= \text{gcd}\,(654321-543210,543210) \\ &= \text{gcd}\,(111111,543210) \\ &= \text{gcd}\,(5 \cdot 111111 - 543210, 111111) \\ &= \text{gcd}\,(12345, 111111) \\
 &= \text{gcd}\,(12345, 12345 \cdot 10 - 111111) \\ &= \text{gcd}\,(12345, 12339) \\ &= \text{gcd}\,(12345-12339, 12339) \\ &= \text{gcd}\,(6,12339). \end{align}We notice that $3 | 12339$ as $3 | 1+2+3+3+9 = 18$, but $12339$ is odd and thus not divisible by $6$.
 The answer is $\boxed{3}$.
 *)

theorem
fixes a b :: nat
assumes h0 : "a = 654321"
and h1 : "b = 543210"
shows  "gcd a b = 3"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer
a_0.informal problem: "What is the greatest common divisor of the two numbers 654321 and 543210? The final answer is 3."
